Motivation

We hear a lot about climate change, in the news, at school, â€¦ One aspect of concern is sea level rise as the ice caps melt. We hear that islands like Tuvalu will be under water completely by the time you reach middle age. We would like to see how Melbourne will fare if the sea levels rise.

Exercise 1

  1. This question needs to be answered by googling for information. What is the expected sea level rise by the end of the 21st century?

Our coastlines

The Australian company NGIS provides a web interface for exploring the coastlines around Australia for risk of sea level rise. You can play around with Melbourne by visiting this site http://coastalrisk.com.au. Enter Melbourne as the site, then select Manual so you can change the prospective sea levels. Sea level rise can be changed between 0-10m, and you can zoom around the map.

Exercise 2

  1. At what sea level does Port Melbourne go completely under?
  2. Name a few suburbs that are most at risk?

Goal

The purpose of this lab is to find data, pull it, clean it, model it, visualise it and build a web app of our own.

Data

Geoscience Australia provides a lot, that is a lot, of resources on its web site. We can pull elevation details for different locations around Australia. From the elevation, we can estimate what parts of the coastline are at risk of going under if sea levels rise.

Exercise 3

You are going to download elevation data for a small part of Melbourne, read it into R, clean it, make it into a data frame, and plot the elevation on a map.

  1. Go to the web site http://www.ga.gov.au/elvis/. Enter Melbourne as the location. Zoom into your favourite location. Choose to download a 25 metre Digital Elevation Model (DEM). It will ask for you to draw on the map to select a chunk. Select a small chunk. Select the output format to be Esri ASCII Grid, and the coordinate system to be WGS84 Lat/Longs. The server will create a data set for you, and send you an email - you will need to enter an email address where you can receive the link to the data. Once youâ€™ve got this, and downloaded the data file, unzip the file on to your computer, just the Desktop is good, and youâ€™ll be ready to move onto the next step.
  2. Start RStudio, and create a Project in the directory that was created when the data was unzipâ€™d.
  3. Read in the your data file name.asc file with this code :

Hint: You donâ€™t need to type all this code out. If you open the lab.Rmd file in the R editor window, you can cut and past the code into a new document to edit and run.

myfile <- "replace this with your data file name.asc"
nc <- as.numeric(scan(myfile, nlines=1, 
                      what=character())[2])
nr <- as.numeric(scan(myfile, skip=1, nlines=1,
                      what=character())[2])
xlc <- as.numeric(scan(myfile, skip=2, nlines=1,
                       what=character())[2])
ylc <- as.numeric(scan(myfile, skip=3, nlines=1,
                       what=character())[2])
cs <- as.numeric(scan(myfile, skip=4, nlines=1,
                      what=character())[2])
w <- scan(myfile, skip=6)
w_df <- data.frame(
  lon=(rep(1:nc, nr)-1)/nc*(nc*cs)+xlc,
  lat=(rep(1:nr, rep(nc, nr))-1)/nr*(-nr*cs)+(ylc+nr*cs),
  elev=w)
summary(w_df)
  1. Discuss with your group what the code x=(rep(1:nc, nr)-1)/nc*(nc*cs)+xlc does, and why we created a variable lon. Write a sentence explaining this.
  2. Report the median of the three variables, lon, lat, elev.
  3. Last step is to plot the elevation data on a map. You need to grab a google map first. This code will find the limits of your data, grab the map, plot it and overlay the elevation on it. (The result should look something like the map above on the right.)

library(dplyr)
library(ggmap)
loc <- c(median(w_df$lon), median(w_df$lat))
m <- get_map(loc, zoom=15, scale=1, color="bw")
p <- ggmap(m)
p + geom_tile(data=w_df,
           aes(x=lon, y=lat, fill=elev), alpha=0.5) +
           scale_fill_viridis() +
           theme_map()

It is also possible to show the elevation as a contour map instead of tiled, with this code below, which would make a map that looks like the plot at right.

p + geom_contour(data=w_df, aes(x=lon, y=lat, z=elev,
                colour=..level..), size=1, bins=5) +
  scale_colour_gradientn("Elevation", colours=viridis(10)) + 
  theme_map()

Elevation

The distribution of elevation in any area will affect how much of it is at flood risk. We can look at the distribution but making a histogram or a density plot.

Exercise 4

  2. Write an R function to do this calculation.

Geolocating

With Googleâ€™s API you can look up post code for any given longitude and latitude. Conversely, for any given address you can look up longitude and latitude. This is used for the app below, to allow users to find their suburb, and explore the coastline. Hereâ€™s the code to do this:

library(ggmap)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
get_lonlat <- function(pc) {
  loc <- geocode(paste0("Vic, ", pc))
  return(loc)
}
get_lonlat("3000")
## Information from URL : http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=Vic,%203000&sensor=false
##        lon       lat
## 1 144.9639 -37.81521

Web app

Now the fun begins. You are going to write your first shiny app1 The full reference site is (http://shiny.rstudio.com/tutorial/).

Exercise 5

  1. The file app.r in the sea_level directory has the code for a basic app on this data. Open this file in your editor window.
  2. Click Run App to run it locally on your computer. Play with the controls. You can enter a post code to focus on your choise of neighbourhood, and also change sea levels.
  3. There are two main functions in the app: ui and server. The ui sets up the user interaction, the text entry for the post code, and the slider for sea level. There are many different choices of input tools that could be used. The server function is the work-horse, running the computations.
  4. You are going to make a couple of small changes to the code get comfortable.
  1. Change the background map to be black and white instead of colour.
  2. Change the tile to a contour display.
  3. Add a slider to change the zoom parameter of the get_map() function.
  1. Your turn to make the app the best it can be. Brainstorm ideas to make a better app. Explore how to make the changes in the code to implement the ideas, and make the changes.2 Do this in small steps so that you can debug your code.
